https://www.reuters.com/live-events/coronavirus-6-id2921484,"During pandemic lockdowns, many couples have spent more time alone together than they could ever have imagined. But in New Mexico, one couple has been practicing self-isolation for decades. Here's more of their story: https://reut.rs/2UeiLCI","Discover Thomson Reuters Directory of sites Login Contact Support Business Markets World Politics TV More for-phone-only for-tablet-portrait-up for-tablet-landscape-up for-desktop-up for-wide-desktop-up See new posts New Zealand says coronavirus 'eliminated' and life can resume without restrictions New Zealand has eliminated transmission of the coronavirus domestically and will lift all containment measures except for border controls, Prime Minister Jacinda Ardern said, making it one of the first countries to do so. Graphics:  Status of upcoming vaccines | Where U.S. cases are on the rise | Tracing COVID-19 | Who should get care first? | Protecting those fighting the virus | Guide to virtual events  Global coronavirus deaths top 400,000 as outbreak grows in Brazil, India: Reuters tally Japan braces for worst postwar economic slump, pandemic tests policy response Fed says beating pandemic is key, but how will it know things are better? Europe's Detroit? Pandemic bursts Toulouse aerospace bubble Mexico stays on maximum virus alert entering second week of 'new normal' Brazil takes down COVID-19 data, hiding soaring death toll Decades of social distance: Meet the American couple who are masters at it During pandemic lockdowns, many couples have spent more time alone together than they could ever have imagined. But in New Mexico, one couple has been practicing self-isolation for decades. Here's more of their story: https://reut.rs/2UeiLCI Advertisement Airlines challenge UK quarantine policy in London's High Court U.S. Lawyers for three of Europe's biggest airlines said the British government's quarantine rules for travellers were irrational and disproportionate at the opening of a High Court challenge to the policy in London on Friday. No new state of emergency as nightlife drives Tokyo's coronavirus spread U.S. Japan will not reintroduce a state of emergency to tackle the novel coronavirus, a government spokesman said on Friday, as cases in Tokyo rose to a two-month high driven by the spread of the virus in the capital's night spots. Advertisement Air France unions bristle as job cuts loom U.S. Air France executives met labour representatives on Friday as union members and staff protested over the airline's plans for around 7,500 job cuts to cope with a collapse in travel due to the coronavirus pandemic. Kim Jong Un says North Korea prevented coronavirus from making inroads U.S. North Korean leader Kim Jong Un told a meeting of the politburo of the ruling Workers Party the North had stopped the novel coronavirus from making inroads in the country, state news agency KCNA said on Friday. Beaches beckon as England to end quarantine for over 50 countries - but not the U.S. U.S. Britain will end coronavirus quarantines for people arriving in England from more than 50 countries, including Germany, France, Spain and Italy - but not the United States - the British government said on Friday. Scotland likely to agree UK's list of low-risk travel countries - Sturgeon U.S. Scottish First Minister Nicola Sturgeon criticised the British government on Friday for ""shambolic"" decision making on opening up to international travel but said it was likely Scotland would agree with the London government's list of low risk countries. Advertisement Health experts cast doubt on India's timeline for COVID vaccine U.S. The chief of India's top clinical research agency said in a leaked letter circulated on Friday it envisaged launching a novel coronavirus vaccine by Aug. 15, prompting scepticism from some health experts who questioned the short timeline. Air France unions braced for job cut talks U.S. The French government on Friday called on Air France to