Exports of products based on BTS are estimated to reach US$1.117 billion, including US$233.98 million of clothing, US$426.64 million cosmetics and 456.49 million food items -- about 1.17 percent of the nation’s total consumer goods exports every year.



“The group’s economic impact has exceeded Psy and Bae Yong-joon (the first-generation Korean Wave actor who gained huge popularity in Japan in the early 2000s),” said Jeong Min, an analyst at the Hyundai think tank.



“More efforts should be made to maximize the BTS effect in the K-pop sector and other industries overall.”



By Lee Ji-yoon (","         ▶주메뉴 바로가기  ▶본문 바로가기         SUBSCRIBE NOW |  LOG IN |  MY PAGE |  SEARCH  MOBILE       검색폼       July 03, 2020             DECODED X    Startups & Investors     Tech    Samsung |  LG |  Mobile & Internet       Blockchain     Markets    Stocks & Bonds |  Deals |  Economy |  Finance |  Office Consulting       Companies    Automobiles |  Retail & Consumer |  Bio & Medicine |  Industrials |  The Boardroom       Second Opinion          Economy    BTS to outpace PyeongChang Winter Olympics’ economic impact    PUBLISHED :December 19, 2018 - 13:54  UPDATED :December 19, 2018 - 14:08              [THE INVESTOR] K-pop sensation BTS is forecast to generate 56 trillion won (US$49.70 billion) in economic benefits over the next 10 years, outpacing the 41.6 trillion won impact of this year’s PyeongChang Winter Olympics, according to the latest report of Hyundai Research Institute on Dec. 19. The local think tank’s report, titled Economic impact of BTS, estimated that the seven-member boy band’s production inducement and added value will reach 4.14 trillion won and 1.42 trillion won, respectively, every year.  Considering the average revenue of Korean midsized firms of 159.17 billion won, BTS’ impact will be almost 26-fold larger. The researchers expect BTS to attract an average of 796,000 foreign tourists to Korea every year, about 7.6 percent of the total 10.41 million people who visited the country last year. Exports of products based on BTS are estimated to reach US$1.117 billion, including US$233.98 million of clothing, US$426.64 million cosmetics and 456.49 million food items -- about 1.17 percent of the nation’s total consumer goods exports every year. “The group’s economic impact has exceeded Psy and Bae Yong-joon (the first-generation Korean Wave actor who gained huge popularity in Japan in the early 2000s),” said Jeong Min, an analyst at the Hyundai think tank. “More efforts should be made to maximize the BTS effect in the K-pop sector and other industries overall.” By Lee Ji-yoon ( jylee@heraldcorp.com )         BACK TO LIST  TOP   EDITOR'S PICKS    Markets     Russia approves HDC’s Asiana takeover, final stage for merger deal cleared: HDC      Companies     Hyundai Mobis invests W25b in US tech funds for future mobility      Markets     Korean PEF inches closer to KDB Life acquisition      Markets     Authorities to expand local companies’ access to financial database      Markets     Kakao Pay Securities highlights fun factor in stock trading      Markets     Watchdog urges full compensation for damages from ponzi-involved Lime fund      Startups & Investors     Seoul emerges top 20 in global startup ecosystem report      Startups & Investors     FSS finds no proof on alleged hacking attempts of Toss: sources       MOST READ    Companies    Hyundai Mobis invests W25b in US tech funds for future mobility     Markets    S. Korea to expand IP financial investment market to W1.3tr by 2024     Markets    Watchdog urges full compensation for damages from ponzi-involved Lime fund     Markets    Russia approves HDC’s Asiana takeover, final stage for merger deal cleared: HDC      Markets    Korean PEF inches closer to KDB Life acquisition     Companies    SK Biopharmaceuticals set to make historic IPO     Markets    Authorities to expand local companies’ access to financial database     Companies    Chunlab launches health care services centering on feces analyzation           ABOUT HERALD CORPORATION  ABOUT  US  LOCATION  CONTACT US  USER AGREEMENT  PRIVACY POLICY  COPYRIGHT POLICY  HERALD OMBUDSMAN  YOUTH PROTECTION POLICY                  Herald Corporation |  CEO : Kwon Chung Won |  Huam-ro 4-gil 10, Yongsan-gu, Seoul, Korea |  Title : The Investor  |  Date of registration : 2015.04.28     Publisher. Editor : Kwon Chung Won |  Chief Privacy Officer & Juvenile Protection Manager  : Yang Sung-jin |  T +82-2-727-0114       FAMILY SITE  GO    THE HERALD BUSINESS  THE KOREA HERALD  THE JUNIOR HERALD  Inspire  TH