https://www.abc.net.au/news/2020-06-30/stark-statistics-reveal-precarious-position-of-women/12404274,"At Helensburgh, south of Sydney, Margaret Hunt is heading off to work.

She's a home care worker, who assists the disabled and the elderly — an essential service that helps vulnerable people live independently.

Since COVID-19 struck, Ms Hunt has lost a third of her paid work, as clients with compromised health isolate and rely on family.

""So, my hours went down from 55-60 hours a fortnight to maybe 35-40,"" she tells the ABC.

Pay rates in her industry are so low that it has left her in the unenviable situation of receiving less than those on social welfare who have no work at all.

""I would be better off on JobSeeker if I could get it,"" she says.

""Better off on unemployment benefits the way they are at the moment.""

Margaret Hunt's plight highlights a key feature of this recession: it's had a disproportionate impact on women — over-represented among the underemployed and in jobs that are often precarious and under-valued.

""It really is a gendered outcome,"" says Professor Marian Baird, who heads the discipline of work at the University of Sydney.

Professor Marian Baird says investing stimulus in social infrastructure would deliver a greater return. ( ABC News: John Gunn )

""We've seen women lose hours of work [in higher proportions than men], they are far more likely to be on zero-hours jobs than men, and secondly, they are far more likely not to be eligible for JobKeeper — so women are really doing it hard in this recession.""

The psychological toll on women has been high too and it has manifested in surprising outcomes.

""It is really quite astonishing actually how this recession has impacted on women and men quite differently,"" observes Professor Baird.

She cites ABS statistics showing women are suffering higher levels of loneliness.

Women have turned to ""what might be seen as ways to soothe their loneliness"", she says, far more than men, increasing their intake of medicines, vitamins … and alcohol.

Women reaching for the bottle has been attributed by some researchers to the twin burden of caring responsibilities and working from home.

But perhaps it is also a symptom of the economic pain of working in low-paid, ""casualised"" industries, where many workers — unable to qualify for the Government's JobKeeper — have been cast out of work.

Survey shows how inhospitable hospitality is

Hospo Voice, a division of the United Workers Union, recently surveyed 1,100 workers from the hospitality industry, where the majority of employees are women and nearly 80 per cent of workers are casual.

The findings were stark.

• 35 per cent said they had to borrow money from friends or family to survive

• 32 per cent had to access super

• 30 per cent had to ask for rent reduction or deferral

• 20 per cent had to go without essentials

• 12 per cent had to turn to charity or a foodbank

• 7 per cent suffered a relationship breakdown

• 7 in 10 were not eligible for JobKeeper

""COVID has underlined existing inequalities in the labour market and vulnerabilities for women,"" says Jo Schofield, national president of the United Workers Union, which represents a range of female-dominated industries including hospitality, aged care, home care, and early childhood education and care.

United Workers Union president Jo Schofield says COVID-19 has exposed existing vulnerabilities in the workforce. ( ABC News: John Gunn )

""What you have seen with hospitality is a mindset that this workforce is disposable.

""Before COVID, these were workers in highly insecure casualised jobs that were low paid. They were also working in a sector that had some of the most egregious forms of wage theft in our economy.""

Claudia Levi knows this all too well. Like so many in the sector, Ms Levi has been paid illegally low wages during her career in hospitality — at one stage, a $19-a-week flat rate including weekends, far under the lawful award wage.

Hospitality worker Claudia Levi turned up for work one day to be told the cafe was not opening and hasn't heard back since. ( ABC News: Curtis Rodda )

She was working as a supervisor at a cafe and event centre in Brunswick, Melbourne, before the pandemic put paid to that income.

""I walked in to start my shift and the owner was there and he said, 'No we are not opening today,' and that was it — never heard from them again,"" she remembers.

""Unfortunately, that's left me with massive bills and no security"", and stress and worry that the establishment may not remain in business to pursue for underpaid wages.

'Hard hats and high vis' attract stimulus dollars

Jo Schofield describes the Government's decision to exclude casual workers from the JobKeeper wage subsidy as gender blind, along with its decision to make old-style infrastructure projects and subsidies for construction a mainstay of the economic stimulus.

Professor Baird agrees.

""Look, the response has been almost a classic, textbook, old-fashioned response of, 'We'll boost the economy through jobs that are for the hard hats and the high-vis vests,'"" she says.

""This is really the wrong way to go and we know from a lot of modelling that you get much more return on your investment these days if you invest in the social infrastructure — care, education, hospitality.""

The nickel-and-dime wages from in-home care give Margaret Hunt a sense of the value government and society places on caring professions like her own.

Committed to her vulnerable clients, Ms Hunt has soldiered on during the disease outbreak, despite the risks to her own health.

The Government has established ""retention bonuses"" for workers in aged care and home care; Ms Hunt would prefer a decent wage.

""Our rates of pay are pitiful,"" she says. ""We are undervalued because I don't think people understand what we actually do.""","     Skip to main content ABC News Homepage Search More from ABC More from ABC Close menu ABC ABC Home News Radio iview Life More Editorial Policies Read our editorial guiding principles Accessibility Help Contact Us About the ABC Privacy Policy Terms of Use © 2020 ABC Just In Politics World Business Analysis Sport Science Health Arts Fact Check Other News Home Coronavirus reveals the precarious position of women in 'disposable workforce' By Stephen Long Posted  3 d days ago Mon Monday  29  Jun June  2020 at 6:48pm , updated  3 d days ago Tue Tuesday  30  Jun June  2020 at 12:35am  Margaret Hunt heads off to work, assisting the disabled and elderly with home care. ( ABC News: John Gunn ) Share Facebook Twitter Article share options Share this on Facebook Twitter LinkedIn Send this by Email Messenger Copy link WhatsApp Print content Print with images and other media Print text only Print Cancel At Helensburgh, south of Sydney, Margaret Hunt is heading off to work. She's a home care worker, who assists the disabled and the elderly — an essential service that helps vulnerable people live independently. Since COVID-19 struck, Ms Hunt has lost a third of her paid work, as clients with compromised health isolate and rely on family. ""So, my hours went down from 55-60 hours a fortnight to maybe 35-40,"" she tells the ABC. Pay rates in her industry are so low that it has left her in the unenviable situation of receiving less than those on social welfare who have no work at all. ""I would be better off on JobSeeker if I could get it,"" she says. ""Better off on unemployment benefits the way they are at the moment."" Margaret Hunt's plight highlights a key feature of this recession: it's had a disproportionate impact on women — over-represented among the underemployed and in jobs that are often precarious and under-valued. ""It really is a gendered