https://www.newstalkzb.co.nz/opinion/barry-soper-is-the-greens-poverty-plan-a-flight-of-fantasy-think-again/,"COMMENT:

It's too easy to dismiss the Greens' Poverty Action Plan as a flight of fantasy - pie in the sky stuff that'll never happen.

But think again.

Making policy like they're planning takes power. And while the Greens may not have it at the moment, it could be a very different story after September 19.

The power in this Government lies with the Winston Peters' handbrake party, New Zealand First, the only party in the formal coalition. The Greens' opinion poll rating has been pretty consistent - above the 5 per cent threshold - whereas Labour's coalition cobbers are struggling at 2 to 3 per cent.

So chances are that after September 19, the Greens could well be where NZ First was after the last election and able to make demands - such as moving tax rates for those earning over a hundred grand to 37 per cent, and those on $150,000 having 42 per cent of their income going into the government's pocket. Currently, they're paying the top rate of 33 per cent.

The money earned there, and on taxing the wealthy (those with assets worth a million) being clobbered with a 1 per cent tax on anything above that - or 2 per cent on anything over $2 million - will go on a universal income. That means paying everyone not in full-time work $325 a week, which would include students.

It's a design for the redistribution of wealth, which Winston Peters says is nuts and nothing more than an envy tax. He likened it in a tweet to the view of Winston Churchill, who said taxing your way to prosperity is like a man standing in a bucket trying to lift himself up by the handle.

Consider this: Our tax brackets move earners on to the top rate once they hit $70,000, hardly enough to make ends meet, certainly with a family in Auckland. Today, 790,000 workers pay the top rate, and that number is growing.

But if you look at who's paying the lion's share in terms of dollars, those earning above a hundred grand a year pay 42 per cent of the income tax take.

If the Greens were serious about people paying a bit more, they should be progressively moving the income brackets above the piddling $70,000 (and forget the nutty universal income which is a disincentive for anyone to end up having anything to envy).

But the Greens are serious. They haven't ruled out their plan being a deal-breaker during coalition negotiations, and without Labour having another potential coalition partner at least they'll have an ear.

Labour was hammered on tax during the last election campaign. They should bear that in mind and distance themselves from it.

Smiling all the way to the ballot box if that doesn't happen will be National, which will be out selling what a Labour/Greens coalition could look like. And so too will be handbrake Peters, who'll be out there reminding the electorate of what he stopped Labour from doing (and there are plenty of examples) including the dead rats he forced the Greens to swallow because of his interference.

But as a reminder to Jacinda Ardern of what could be on the horizon, Julie Anne Genter tweeted: This is what transformational really looks like.",
https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2020/06/29/coronavirus-positive-good-news-round-up-song-peace-scotland/?utm_content=telegraph&utm_medium=Social&utm_campaign=Echobox&utm_source=Twitter#Echobox=1593431376,"A song for peace from Scotland this Monday, with musicians from all across the world being encouraged to get involved in a new international song for peace.

Aberdeen University lecturer Neil McLennan and Scottish fiddler Thoren Ferguson launched the iSingForPeace project on the anniversary of the Treaty of Versailles, which brought an official end to the First World War.

The national orchestra of Scotland is among contributors to 'Stronger for the Storm', with vocals from Scottish singer, songwriter and broadcaster Fiona Kennedy.

The project will culminate with a special performance on the afternoon of Remembrance Sunday, and in the meantime aims to ""reflect, remember and unite"" as a global community.

If you're missing Wimbledon - which should now be under way - there will be highlights shown throughout this week from tennis tournaments gone by. The great Federer-Nadal clash from 2008 is among the games you won't want to miss while serving up the strawberries and cream.

It goes without saying that The Telegraph's award-winning sports reporters will also be serving up ace content on matches gone by, in order to quench your tennis thirst.

As a survey finds that 53 per cent are now considering cycling to work, Transport for London has predicted that the surge in those preferring pedal power could be tenfold. Mark Bailey has more on the huge health benefits - which could lengthen your lifespan while maintaining your mood.

And the UK will come together this weekend for the 'biggest thank you ever' for coronavirus key workers. Broadcasters will pause their transmissions at 5pm on July 5as people across the country will clap not just the NHS but other workers who have helped to keep services and community networks going throughout the crisis.

Make sure to pop the kettle on - as neighbours, family and friends are encouraged to come together for a socially distanced cuppa while reflecting on the bonds that have kept us going in recent months.

Here’s Harriet with the rest of today’s good news:

The neighbours of a 16-year-old who was ""devastated"" when her prom was cancelled threw a surprise street party to celebrate instead. The community in Andover, Hampshire, decorated the street with fairy lights and balloons for Stacie Stroud, who has cerebral palsy and epilepsy Ms Stroud’s sister did her hair and make up, her grandfather picked her up in his yellow van and the neighbours cheered for her arrival. Her mum said: ""We had a bit of a socially-distanced disco in the evening… She cried when she arrived.""

A volunteer sewing squad in the United States has distributed more than 55,000 masks to vulnerable people in three months. The group, Auntie Sewing Squad, has 800 people sewing masks across the country.

Dozens of German doctors will be hosted for free on the Greek island of Kos from Monday, in “recognition and gratitude for their contribution in combating the coronavirus”. The flight of 170 doctors arrives two days before the country officially reopens its regional airport to passenger traffic.

Two pig farmers in Suffolk have successfully fed one million bees by turning over half their land – the equivalent of 83 football pitches – to wildflowers. The brothers, Mark and Paul Hayward, planted nectar-rich flowers and a seed mix of phacelia, sainfoin, birds-foot trefoil, alsike clover, musk mallow, campium and vetch. Paul said to Farming UK: “We are taking a very minor role in helping society restore a more favourable balance and this starts with plant diversity to encourage insects, bees, small mammals, and birds.”

By Harriet Barber

