ation                      Log In Using Your Account  Log In      Don't have an account?  Sign Up Today                My Account  Dashboard  Profile  Saved items   Logout                           Search                 Awards  About Us  Contact Us  Return Policy / Privacy Policy  Terms and Conditions  e-Edition  NEWS  Local   Crime  Police Logs  Education  Politics  Veterans  State  National  News Tips  Coronavirus  Local Coronavirus News  Douglas Public Health Network  Centers for Disease Control and Prevention  World Health Organization  National Institutes of Health  SPORTS  Preps   College  UCC  Ducks  Beavers  Outdoors  AP Sports  OPINION  Letters to the Editor  Editorials  Guest Columns  Submit a Letter  Submit a Guest Column  LIFE   Family   Business Directory  Camps  Child Care  Resale  Farms & Pumpkin Patches  Birthday Parties  Family Services  Health  Schools  Calendar  Health  Home and Garden  ENTERTAINMENT  A&E;  Food  Movie Reviews  Calendar  Submit an event  Submit your photos  BUSINESS  OBITS  Submit Obit  CLASSIFIEDS  Autos  Real Estate  Service Directory  Employment                                                                 More CARES assistance is good news      Mail Tribune   Jun 27, 2020    Jun 27, 2020               Facebook        Twitter        WhatsApp        SMS        Email                  Facebook        Twitter        WhatsApp        SMS        Email        Print        Save                Gov. Kate Brown has belatedly agreed to send federal CARES Act funding to Jackson County and others to help ease the blow of the novel coronavirus shutdown. That’s welcome news, although it won’t cover all the economic damage the county suffered. But it will allow some assistance to businesses hit hard by the closure order. In all, the county expects to receive at least $7.7 million. Most of that money will go to reimburse the county’s direct expenses for providing medical gear such as personal protective equipment, virus testing and contact tracing. The county spent nearly $1.5 million from April 1 to May 15. County Administrator Danny Jordan estimates direct medical expenses through the end of the year will total about $4 million, but it could be more if the number of COVID-19 cases shows a dramatic increase. The rest of the federal aid, about $2.3 million, can be used to help businesses affected by the pandemic. Brown and state legislative leaders initially limited how much money they would distribute and restricted the use of the money to reimbursement for direct costs. At the same time, Portland-area counties were given federal aid directly because of their size, and permitted to use it for economic aid to businesses as well as direct costs. County commissioners here and in other smaller counties protested the state’s decision, and the League of Oregon Cities and Association of Oregon Counties went to bat on their behalf as well. Leaders in this region and other parts of the state have long objected to what they see as preferential treatment given to the Portland area, which has more representation in the Legislature because of its population.  What was especially galling about this situation was Jackson County’s success in keeping the number of COVID-19 cases low, while Portland and other cities saw much larger numbers. Brown and state leaders apparently listened to the concerns of the smaller counties and responded by doing the right thing and disbursing more money. That doesn’t mean the county will be fully compensated for its losses, which will include millions in various taxes and other sources of income affected by the coronavirus shutdown. And $2.3 million won’t go very far toward keeping businesses afloat and able to pay employees. Congress still may come through with additional stimulus money this summer, but that’s not guaranteed. Meanwhile, Southern Oregon residents must continue to do their part to limit the spread of this virus by practicing social distancing and wearing face masks in public. That will allow reopened businesses to keep operating, which will do more to stimulate the economy than any government assistance. The worst that could happen would be to stop taking precautions and cause a big increase in infections, forcing officials to retreat from reopening and reimpose closure orders.    React to this story:          Love     0     Funny     0     Wow     0     Sad     0     Angry     0                Facebook        Twitter        WhatsApp        SMS        Email        Print        Save                                Earth Day still bringing us together, 50 years later   Stuart Liebowitz
